Best way to test pdf-rag-pipeline is in 3 layers: unit tests, API auth checks, then end-to-end ingest/query.

1) Quick unit tests (fastest sanity check)
From repo root:

cd pdf-rag-pipeline
source .venv/bin/activate
pytest -q tests/test_prefilter.py tests/test_safety.py
These cover:

page pre-filtering (test_prefilter.py)
safety logic (test_safety.py)
2) Run the API locally
cd pdf-rag-pipeline
cp .env.example .env   # first time only
source .venv/bin/activate
pip install -r requirements.txt
uvicorn api.main:app --reload --port 8090
API routes:

POST /api/v1/query (any authenticated user)
POST /api/v1/ingest (admin role required)
3) Configure .env properly
Minimum important vars in pdf-rag-pipeline/.env:

MONGO_URI / MONGO_DB
JWT_SECRET, JWT_ALGORITHM, JWT_ISSUER (must match backend token config)
LLM config:
LLM_PROVIDER=openai + OPENAI_API_KEY, or
LLM_PROVIDER=gemini + GEMINI_API_KEY
PDF_DIR=./pdfs (or your custom folder)
4) API smoke test with real JWT
Use a JWT issued by your backend (after login).

Query endpoint
curl -X POST "http://localhost:8090/api/v1/query" \
  -H "Authorization: Bearer <USER_JWT>" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"question":"What are the common symptoms of dengue?"}'
Ingest endpoint (admin only)
curl -X POST "http://localhost:8090/api/v1/ingest" \
  -H "Authorization: Bearer <ADMIN_JWT>"
Expected:

non-admin token on /ingest -> 403 Admin role required
admin token -> {"status":"ingestion started", ...}
5) End-to-end flow to verify retrieval
Put one or two PDFs in PDF_DIR
Call /api/v1/ingest with admin token
Wait briefly (ingest runs in background task)
Ask a question via /api/v1/query that should match PDF content
Confirm answer/source are returned
